snippet.textDisplay: Makes me imagine walking into a small rusty brown hut, from which all of my family stand huddled around a smokey black furnace. The warmth brushes against my face and embraces my cheeks. The aroma of burning hay delights my senses; an aroma with history and a past, like the inside of an old book. I sit before the furnace, staring deeply into the fire. Fatigue from a day of preventing the reign of lost souls suddenly captures me, and the roaring fire begins to blur, fading slowly into darkness.

snippet.textDisplay:
David Wise's most praised tracks consisted of in the 90s. Most of the works I refer to being not his best are actually from more GBA and beyond.
Even if that was reversed though I'd still take into account the old stuff seeing as many of these composer's best works have been from the past. By said logic, I should consider them bad because their quality has lackened over the years? I'm gonna take the good with the bad, and not single out any one type and ignore the other.

snippet.textDisplay:
A composer should be praised for the amount of good songs they have. For example, If one person has 15 good songs, and another person has 17 equally good songs, then that composer is better.
Also, you have to take the time period into consideration. Yeah, a composer may have some bad songs, but if they're from 10 years ago, and they have since improved dramatically then it isn't really a song written by the CURRENT them and should no longer be acknowledged at all.

snippet.textDisplay: That's not too fair. What if a composer has one soundtrack, greatest ever, but then they also made all of the worst soundtracks of all time? 1/11 would not make them the best, even if that one is insanely good. Not to say David Wise has a ton of bad on his credits, but to ignore the less than good is becoming a mindless fanboy. It's normal to like some stuff and dislike others. Yasunori Mitsuda is my favorite but I'll admit he has some crap on his resume.
